04736nam a22007695i 9780674044661DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221998mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740446617 a10.4159/97806740446612doi  a(DE-B1597)574555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHD2755.5 ǂb V472 1998eb 7aBUS0350002bisacsh04a338.881 aVernon, Raymond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Hurricane's Eye :bThe Troubled Prospects of Multinational Enterprises /cRaymond Vernon. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1 SETTING THE CONTEXT -- t2 TENSIONS IN THE BACKGROUND -- t3 INSIDE THE EMERGING ECONOMIES -- t4 INSIDE THE INDUSTRIALIZED ECONOMIES -- t5 THE STRUGGLE OVER OPEN MARKETS -- t6 RIGHTING THE BALANCE -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world's multinational enterprises face a spell of rough weather, political economist Ray Vernon argues, not only from the host countries in which they have established their subsidiaries, but also from their home countries. Such enterprises--a few thousand in number, including Microsoft, Toyota, IBM, Siemens, Samsung, and others--now generate about half of the world's industrial output and half of the world's foreign trade; so any change in the relatively benign climate in which they have operated over the past decade will create serious tensions in international economic relations. The warnings of such a change are already here. In the United States, interests such as labor are increasingly hostile to what they see as the costs and uncertainties of an open economy. In Europe, those who want to preserve the social safety net and those who feel that the net must be dismantled are increasingly at odds. In Japan, the talk of "hollowing out" takes on a new urgency as the country's "lifetime employment" practices are threatened and as public and private institutions are subjected to unaccustomed stress. The tendency of multinationals in different countries to find common cause in open markets, strong patents and trademarks, and international technical standards has been viewed as a loss of national sovereignty and a weakening of the nation-state system, producing hostile reactions in home countries. The challenge for policy makers, Vernon argues, is to bridge the quite different regimes of the multinational enterprise and the nation-state. Both have a major role to play, and yet must make basic changes in their practices and policies to accommodate each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCompetition, International. 0aConcurrence internationale. 0aEntreprises multinationales. 0aGroupes de pression. 0aHost countries (Business)xEconomic aspects. 0aInternational business enterprises. 0aPays d'accueil (Commerce international)xPolitique économique. 0aPressure groups. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674044661zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674044661423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674044661/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK